1. What is API Gateway?

An API Gateway is a server that sits between clients and backend services.

It acts as a single entry point for:

Web apps
Mobile apps
Third-party clients
Internal services

Instead of exposing every microservice directly, clients communicate only with the API Gateway.

Without API Gateway
Client → Catalog Service
Client → User Service
Client → Payment Service
Client → Order Service

Problems:

Too many endpoints
Hard to secure
Hard to manage auth
Hard to monitor
Tight coupling
With API Gateway
Client → API Gateway → Services

Benefits:

One public endpoint
Centralized security
Load balancing
Authentication
Logging
Monitoring
Routing



2. Why API Gateway is Needed
In Microservices Architecture

When an application has many services:

User Service
Product Service
Cart Service
Payment Service
Notification Service

Clients should not directly call each service.

API Gateway solves:
Problem	Solution
Too many APIs	Single entry point
Authentication repeated everywhere	Centralized auth
No monitoring	Central logs
Direct exposure	Hidden internal services
Traffic spikes	Rate limiting
Scaling issues	Load balancing